                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">838.51/3418: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Finley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-10T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 10, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>63. My telegram No. 62, August 9, 1 p.m.<note n="39" xml:id="d554fn39">Not
                        printed.</note> De la Rue at Leger’s request is again writing to Eberstadt
                    in an endeavor to elucidate the viewpoint of the Haitian Government and to find
                    out whether he is prepared to proceed on any other basis than that which he
                    seems most unwittingly to have envisaged. Pending receipt of his reply Leger
                    told De la Rue that he would prefer not to proceed with protocol
                    negotiations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Finley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
